05974nam a22011295i 9780691225517DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20212004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912255177 a10.1515/97806912255172doi  a(DE-B1597)576274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBL1241.44b.F855 2003 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a294.5/61/0954821 aFuller, C. J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Renewal of the Priesthood :bModernity and Traditionalism in a South Indian Temple /cC. J. Fuller. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b4 line illus. 4 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tNote on Transliteration -- tKey to Figures 1 and 2 -- tOne. The Priests and the Minakshi Temple’s Renovation Ritual -- tTwo. Rights, Duties, and Work -- tThree. Family and Domestic Life -- tFour. The Agamas and Priestly Education -- tFive. Religious Politics and the Priests -- tSix. Modernity, Traditionalism, and the State -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMuch has changed for the priests at the Minakshi Temple, one of the most famous Hindu temples in India. In The Renewal of the Priesthood, C. J. Fuller traces their improving fortunes over the past 25 years. This fluidly written book is unique in showing that traditionalism and modernity are actually reinforcing each other among these priests, a process in which the state has played a crucial role. Since the mid-1980s, growing urban affluence has seen more people spend more money on rituals in the Minakshi Temple, which is in the southern city of Madurai. The priests have thus become better-off, and some have also found new earnings opportunities in temples as far away as America. During the same period, due partly to growing Hindu nationalism in India, the Tamilnadu state government's religious policies have become more favorable toward Hinduism and Brahman temple priests. More priests' sons now study in religious schools where they learn authoritative Sanskrit ritual texts by heart, and overall educational standards have markedly improved. Fuller shows that the priests have become more "professional" and modern-minded while also insisting on the legitimacy of tradition. He concludes by critiquing the analysis of modernity and tradition in social science. In showing how the priests are authentic representatives of modern India, this book tells a story whose significance extends far beyond the confines of the Minakshi Temple itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aHindu priestszIndiazMadurai. 0aMīnākṣī (Hindu deity)xCultzIndiazMadurai. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAgamas.  aAgamic education.  aAgamic schools: Allur.  aBesant, Annie.  aBharatiya Janata Party (BJP).  aChidambaram temple.  aCongress Party.  aDakshinamurti.  aDharma Rakshana Sabha.  aEkamranatha temple.  aFrench Institute of Pondicherry.  aGopalan, Rama.  aHindu nationalism.  aHindu reformism.  aJustice Party.  aKalugumalai temple.  aKumbeshwara temple, land, tax-free grants of.  aMinakshi Temple.  aMinakshi and Sundareshwara.  aMurugan (Skanda, Subrahmanya).  aMylapore Group.  aNayaka kings.  aNon-Resident Indians (NRI).  aParashakti.  aRashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh (RSS).  aSarasvati.  aSubramania Aiyar, S.  aTamil archanas.  aTirupati temple.  aTirupparankundram temple.  aTiruvannamalai temple.  aTiruvarur temple.  aVishwa Hindu Parishad (VHP).  aanti-Brahmanism.  aeconomic liberalization.  amiddle class.  amoder